<subSubSection pageId="45" pageNumber="46" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="45.[264,1322,633,939]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
Remarks. This large, nearly world wide, genus inhabits mostly tropical regions. It is well represented in the Neotropics with 100 varified species now reported. Of these, nearly 1/2 (46) is from the West Indies, with 21 from Hispaniola, largely 
<collectingCountry box="[1023,1199,713,739]" name="Dominican Republic" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">the Dominican</collectingCountry>
Republic, and the remaining 25 the other islands. We also report the discovery of the male of 
<taxonomicName authority="Scarbrough (1984)" authorityName="Scarbrough" authorityYear="1984" box="[264,798,793,819]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cinnamomeus">
<emphasis box="[264,559,793,818]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Ommatius cinnamomeus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Scarbrough, A. G." box="[572,798,793,819]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" pagination="131 - 149" refId="ref42685" refString="Scarbrough, A. G. (1984) Synopsis of Ommatius Wiedemann (Diptera: Asilidae) from Hispaniola. Journal of the New York Entomological Society 92, 131 - 149." type="journal article" year="1984">Scarbrough (1984)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and illustrate its terminalia. The genus is distinguished by the pectinate style. Many species prefer tips of bare branches of woody or herbaceous vegetation along margins of sunlit clearings in, paths and roads through forested areas.
</paragraph>
